  "prompt": "What does it mean when you have blood clots but no period?",
  "response": "Experiencing blood clots without a menstrual period can be concerning and may indicate several potential conditions. Here are some possibilities:\n\n1. **Pregnancy**: If you are sexually active, one possibility is early pregnancy. In some cases, women may experience implantation bleeding, which can include light bleeding or spotting accompanied by small clots.\n\n2. **Hormonal Imbalances**: Conditions like polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) or thyroid disorders can lead to irregular menstrual cycles, including the absence of periods (amenorrhea) and sometimes unusual bleeding.\n\n3. **Miscarriage**: If you are pregnant, blood clots and bleeding can be signs of miscarriage, especially if accompanied by cramping or significant pain.\n\n4. **Ectopic Pregnancy**: This occurs when a fertilized egg implants outside the uterus, often leading to abnormal bleeding and pain.\n\n5. **Uterine Fibroids or Polyps**: These growths can cause abnormal bleeding or spotting even when a woman is not having her period.\n\n6. **Endometriosis**: This condition involves tissue similar to the lining of the uterus growing outside of it, which can cause irregular bleeding, pain, and other symptoms.\n\n7. **Infections**: Certain infections can lead to abnormal bleeding patterns, including sexually transmitted infections (STIs).\n\n8. **Blood Clotting Disorders**: Rarely, underlying clotting disorders could lead to unusual bleeding or clotting patterns.\n\nIf you are experiencing blood clots without a period, it is essential to consult a healthcare professional for a proper evaluation and diagnosis. They may recommend tests, such as blood tests, ultrasound, or other imaging studies, to determine the underlying cause.",
